When people try to box you in and define who and what you’re allowed to be, my question is….

Says who?

If you have a dream, a goal, a project in mind, go for it.

Prepare, plan, and execute. You’ll be amazed what happens next regardless of outcome.

My hope is everyone sees the greatness within them. It won’t look the same for us all, but I promise you that it’s in there.

Nobody can convince me that not everyone is important and needed for us to all thrive 🫡

Our time is now 🫡

It’s always the same story. This type of racism gets brushed off as a “joke”. Then we’re gaslit and told we’re “too sensitive”.

What’s sensitive is not being able to take justified criticism and make lame excuses.

Let me be clear, it’s not funny, grow up.

The “apology” is the actual joke. Pointing to the couple month old DEI program as his evidence that he’s not racist is actually evidence that he shouldn’t be chancellor, but enrolled in an actual DEI course.

An apology isn’t riddled with excuses, but rather shown through action.

Asians are not sensitive for standing up for ourselves. We’re just fed up with the racism and taking a stand.

Because there is a difference between not standing up for ourselves and being told to sit down.

There is a difference between being silent and being told to shut up.
Great to have Secretary Pete Buttigieg visit the Mayor and City Hall the other day 🫡

“There is a difference between not standing up for yourself and being told to sit down.

There is a difference between not speaking up for yourself and being told to shut up.”

This is a message I have for the all communities, not just my own. 

It’s also a huge privilege and honor to not just speak, but be heard. For too long, those in my community have been cast aside and ignored, but not anymore.

We’re not going to apologize for who we are. We are unapologetically Asian and we’re not going anywhere 🫡

Praying for Damar Hamlin.

For those unaware, Buffalo Bills player took a horrific hit and had to receive CPR on the field. It was clear that his life was in danger.

The Commissioner has the authority to end any game at any time. The league chose to order the players to warm up with the intention to restart the game. 

They were given 5 minutes.

It should never been a decision that the teams had to force the league to make, which is to end the game immediately and focus solely on Damar Hamlin’s life. He is all that matters.

Praying for Damar and his family 🙏

This was supposed to be a day about celebration. A day to wish health, prosperity, and good fortune for the upcoming year after letting go of the past one. But today, our community woke up to this devastation.

While this is very much a developing situation, we do know that Monterey Park is a predominately Asian community. We do know that Lunar New Year celebrations happened and scheduled to continue in the morning. 

While the majority of society and media have moved on and decided our stories are not worth covering, we remind you that it’s not true.

At the same time, what’s most important are the precious lives lost. The lives that are in both stable and critical condition. And of course, their loved ones.

We as a society are so broken.

Sending love to everyone and especially to the families who lost loved ones, as well as those still in stable and critical condition. Praying for you all 🙏

My remarks to the crowd that gathered today to honor the lives lost and their grieving families.

The violence that the community has faced has been relentless and the pain that stems from it will likely last generations.

And while my message wasn’t a direct address to what happened, it was more so one to remind our community that we’re worthy and that we’ll get through this together. 

One day at a time. One step at a time. But always together and always with love.

As I prepared to speak this past weekend at the vigil for the victims of Monterey Park and Half Moon Bay, I kept thinking about the immense suffering that’s constantly ignored in our communities.

I think about @lee_minjin’s words, “our bodies are not designed to absorb and process this much violence, loss, and grief.”

I think about the lack of resources due to language barriers, not knowing how to navigate systems, and how so many suffer more when they don’t have to.

I think about how hurt and traumatized someone has to be to inflict so much harm onto others.

I think about the exhaustion of our community from constantly being in a state of grief and mourning.

I think about the feeling of exacerbation from always being ignored, cast aside, and told it’s not our turn.

I also think about what could be.

I won’t pretend like I have all the answers, because I don’t. But I do know that we deserve better than this. I do know that we don’t have to accept this as our present and future. I do know that we are our greatest hope.

We’re going to get through this and we’re going to do it together.

Much love ❤️

Also, I wanted to call out some community organizations to support because they’re doing the work. So here are a few: @cpajustice @asiancdc @ataskboston @vietaid @aarw.boston @cmaalowell

Especially during an era with so much hate, I feel it’s essential to go back to the basics and realize what’s truly important in life.

People want to be seen, heard, valued, and most of all loved. It’s also something we haven’t always felt and receive to different degrees, or sometimes don’t receive at all. Like most things, love is complicated.

Love also comes in different forms, such as languages. Therefore, there are many times it can be lost in translation and misinterpreted due to miscommunication. That leaves behind a lot of hurts that can last generations.

But the thing is, love is also the most powerful feeling in existence. Love can heal generational wounds. Love can transcend cultural barriers and bring people together who were once enemies. Love can rebuild a lost world and usher in a new era of hope and possibilities.

Love has no bounds.

So wherever you are in the world, know that you are loved. Maybe not always in the way you can feel it, but know that you are.

Much love ❤️

#valentinesday #valentines #love

Are you listening to understand or are you listening to respond?

So many of the problems we face are because of misunderstandings that stem from miscommunication or miscommunication that stems from misunderstandings.

We also often argue and fight with each other because we may be talking about the same topic but having very different discussions. That can be because we have different perspectives, definitions and understandings of words and context, motivations, and identities. The ways in which we experience and are impacted throughout life can drastically influence the way we live and treat one another. 

Which brings me back to the questions I posed. Are you listening to understand or listening to respond?

Being better at listening is something we can all improve. By no means will it solve all our problems. I’m not dumb enough to think that. But it will at least give us a fighting chance to resolve some of the problems and heal some of our wounds. Because too often I see us going after people who generally align with each other, when in reality, they’re more allies than not.

Again, listening alone won’t fix the world. But it will at least give us a starting block to build the foundation upon.

Much love 🫡❤️

Also, always listen to Jerry. The man is a wealth of knowledge and wisdom. I’ve learned so much from him over the years and grateful to have him in my life 🙏

Breaking news: Current Deputy Secretary of Labor, Julie Su will officially be nominated by President Biden to potentially serve as the next Secretary of Labor.

Deputy Secretary Su served as the Secretary of Labor for the State of California prior to her current role in the Biden/Harris Administration.

It’s so important that AAPIs are at the decision making table. There is no better advocate for us than us. While her responsibility will be to the workers of this country, too often, the needs and perspectives of our community are missing. We make up nearly 8 percent of the total population but approximately 1.4 percent for all elected officials. Julie Su would be the only Cabinet level official from our community.

And massive shoutout to everyone who advocated behind the scenes to make this happen. There was a lot of organizing and collaboration to make our voices heard. Of course, it was in support of the rightful choice and amazing leader, in Julie Su.

Image and News credit to: @nbcasianamerica

삼일운동 is a day we honor the lives and sacrifices of the over 2,000,000 that protested during Japanese occupation.

A day we honor our ancestors who fought to preserve our history, names, food, culture, and identities.

A day of remembrance so that the world doesn’t forget who we are and where we come from.

Love and respect to my people and our ancestors 🇰🇷

대한민국 만세

Note: I want to be extremely clear. It is not possible to capture the depth of what Koreans experienced under occupation in a single post. It can’t even be captured in an entire series of books. Nor can I, ever, speak on behalf of the entire Korean diaspora, especially our ancestors.

All I try to do is speak from my perspective and try and respect my heritage as much as I can. Many non-Koreans are completely unaware of Korean history and my hope is this post will inspire them to learn more in depth 🙏

@daviannguyen, the founder of @jackfroot @jackfrootnews @jackfrooteats has passed away. To many, he was the heartbeat behind Jackfroot, a source of news and a community that many in the AAPI Community and those that love us depended on. @daviannguyen wasn’t a part of MSM, he wasn’t super well funded, but he used his platform the best way he knew how. This man cared and he cared deeply about people.

He was someone who understood the weight of lifting up the community and fighting the good fight. He checked in on others and was always so supportive.

I’m devastated for his family. I’m devastated for our community. I’m devastated for the loss of a beautiful human gone too soon.

I hope you found the rest and peace you deserve, brother ❤️

Sending love to all who loved @daviannguyen and the @jackfroot community. 

📷 cred: @blackandasiansoulsunite

Honored to meet Loida Lewis. She is a pioneer who revived a billion dollar company that was in the red, after taking over as CEO once her husband passed. Her late husband, Reginald Lewis was the first Black person to build a billion dollar company in the US.

Loida was also the first Asian to pass the New York bar without having attended law school. She was one of the first to pass at all, since immigrants were banned until the 70’s from practicing law.

Ms. Lewis’s extensive achievements have spanned decades as she is now 81, but she has no plans to slow down. She just released her book, “Why should guys have all the fun” and still very active as a power player in the world.

Thank you to Jennifer for inviting me to meet with Loida one on one. Who herself is an incredible leader and powerbroker herself.

Most important speech I’ve given was the commencement speech to the 8th graders at Murphy High School in Dorchester

I told them how I’ve spoken in front of hundreds of people and have had millions view my videos, but I was never more nervous than today.

Because when I speak to adults, they almost have to clap. But 8th graders are brutally honest and will let you know if your message isn’t hitting. More importantly, they’re not just our future, but our present. 

I spoke about 4 key lessons:
• Discover your why
• Redefine success and failure
• Ask questions, be teachable, always be curious
• Be unapologetically yourself

I get asked if I get nervous speaking on stage like I did at @ascendleader for @1587sneakers and the answer is, “yes….but”

It’s that confidence that comes with knowing I’ve done the work, that I’ve prepared, and no matter what, say it with my entire chest.

There is no way to guarantee you’ll win the crowd over. But you can guarantee you’ll lose them if you aren’t fully bought into what you’re going to say.

As with anything in life, know your why, focus on your purpose, and have unwavering conviction in what you stand for.

Do that and go rock that stage 🫡

Swipe through and which was your favorite? 🫡

1. Crème button down with cropped pants and tube socks

Something I think about often if how to get people to seek to understand one another. To me, that understanding and perspective will change the world

When the @naaap_boston team asked me what topic I’d like to speak on at the @naaap_national convention, I specifically asked for, “Black and Asian Solidarity”.

Because why be at the table, and not advocate for the difficult, but necessary conversations.

So we were graced by the presence of Courtney Henderson of the Brockton NAACP, and President Emeritus of Chinese Progressive Association, Suzanne Lee.

Both have been longtime leaders, with a deep desire to build bridges between communities.

To be honest, you can’t help but be nervous. You can never predict how the audience or even panelists will do or say. But it couldn’t have gone better.

We were honest, vulnerable, genuine, and compassionate. We shared perspectives that opened up people’s hearts. Shed light on new information people didn’t know. And genuinely believe hope was formed in that room.

By no means was one conversation among 100+ people going to resolve generations of pain. But you have to start somewhere.

Grateful to the NAAAP Boston Leadership team for believing. Honored to share the stage with Courtney and Suzanne.

Much love ❤️

Dont let anyone tell you who you can and cannot be. We need your fullselves to build the world we deserve 🙏

I used to think leadership was the person who stood on stage and gave the inspiration speeches. But I was wrong.

Leadership is making sure the people around you feel empowered. That they’re growing and reaching their potential. Which is done when leaders help build the conditions for people to thrive.

Leaders put others first and share opportunities because they understand everyone wins when everyone grows.

Leaders find joy in watching others achieve goals they were unsure they’d reach. Because it’s about the mission, not the individual.

So find the people who empower others. Who understand that there is plenty of space for all of us. Who seek to share opportunities and value all those around them. 

And often times, you won’t find those leaders on stage. They’re usually right next to you or right behind you, making sure you succeed.

10-24-23 is the day we laid Chinatown and City of Boston legend, Uncle Frank to rest. 

For the last several decades, nothing happened in Chinatown without Uncle Frank knowing or Uncle Frank approving. Every decision, every chess move he made was with Chinatown and it’s community in mind. He was Chinatown.

There are thousands of stories of how he changed peoples lives. He even changed mine. 

Back when I was in high school, I went to a banquet in Chinatown. I noticed how all these powerful leaders kept going up to this one small Chinese American man to pay respect. For the first time in my life, I saw an Asian man be revered so much by non Asians. It blew my mind.

Years later as I got my start in government, I came to realize why that man was so well respected. For decades, Uncle Frank organized a community that for generations had no political power, to becoming one of the most respected power brokers this city had ever seen. 

Years ago, the city was in extremely difficult times financially. Many employees were asked to make sacrifices and many were furloughed or let go. Uncle Frank was one of a handful who volunteered to forgo his salary so others on his team could be paid. 

When a family in Chinatown was struggling, he would quietly make sure they were taken care of. When someone needed a job, he worked his network to get them an opportunity. When then City Councilor Michelle Wu ran for Mayor, he made it clear, she’s the one, get in line. To him, he valued loyalty above all else. Not to him, but to the community. 

However, Uncle Franks legacy isn’t fully written just yet. There are so many who he has touched, taught, and inspired who continue to live out his legacy and build upon the foundation he built.

As Mayor Wu said in her eulogy, this is not a goodbye, because as Uncle Frank would say, “there’s more work to do.”

Dear Boston,

It’s been one hell of a ride. But after 32 years, it’s time to say goodbye and start a new chapter.

12 years ago, I got started on my path in politics when I was inspired by a Harvard Professor, who was running for US Senate. So I volunteered on Elizabeth Warrens campaign. Not knowing just how much her career and those on her team would impact mine.

A year later, I interned for State Rep. Kay Khan. She is a wonderful person, who cares deeply about every constituent. She was the first politician to take a chance on me.

On my second day, I’d get a call at the office summoning me to the Speakers Office. So I rushed up there, and greeting me at the door, was Miss Mattie Miles. Lord knows how much she means to me now. She made sure I calmed down and escorted me to the office.

That day changed my life. I met Speaker Bob DeLeo for the first time. He would become the longest serving Speaker in Massachusetts history, but he was also a father figure, and mentor I desperately needed. Wherever we went together, he always made sure I was respected and had a seat at the table. I owe that man everything.

After graduating from grad school, where I also served as the Chair of the Massachusetts Asian American Commission, and on the AAPI Steering Committee on Michelle Wu’s Mayoral Campaign, I joined Team Sonia.

This was my first full time job on a campaign, and it was a historic one. We didn’t get the final result we wanted, but we got the first woman of color and first Asian American on the ballot for Governor in Massachusetts. We had an extraordinary team, and despite all odds, put up a valiant fight.

And then Mayor Wu came calling. I met the extraordinary Tiffany Chu, her Chief of Staff for soup dumplings and was asked to officially join the WuTrain. I played it off like I needed to think about it, but I always knew I’d serve Mayor Wu in an official capacity. The honor of a lifetime to serve in her administration.

But there are opportunities that come your way and you know in your heart it’s time. As this chapter ends in Boston, I’ll be starting my next one in Washington DC.

To my Boston fam, thank you. You’ll always be home 🙏

Join me next Thursday at Carrie Nation from 5:30-8:00 PM 🫡

I would love to see as many people as possible so I can thank you personally.

Please DM me your email so I can send you an invitation to RSVP. That’s super helpful for headcount!

The first significant wave of immigration started on January 13, 1903, when a shipload of Korean immigrants arrived in Hawaii.

So this year, @thecouncilka honored those that came before us and paved the way. Because 120 years later, we are stronger than ever and that is only possible because of the sacrifices of our older generations.

The organization is a collection of the most influential Korean Americans across the country. From industry titans, political leaders, and visionaries. It’s truly an honor to be a member of CKA as we work to continue paving the way forward for us all.

Honored to share my story and journey to the next generation of BIPOC students that are a part of the LB family.

Leadership Brainery, founded by my brothers, @jonathanforall and @jr.derrick aims to help close wealth and opportunity gaps by increasing access to advanced education for underrepresented communities. So whenever they ask me for anything, it’s always an immediate yes.

I myself, never imagined I’d go to grad school. I was never a “good student”. Graduating from undergrad with a 2.39 GPA, I eliminated myself from consideration. The fear of rejection and lack of self worth predetermined my decision. But after several mentors encouraged me to at least try, I understood that the worst that could happen is learning from the process and finding my next path regardless of the outcome.

So I applied. Two and a half years later, I not only received two scholarships, but graduated with two Masters and a 3.5 GPA. I’ve since been able to apply both degrees into work that I care deeply about. Workin for the Wu Administration and co-founding a sneaker company to celebrate my community. Being able to make an impact, just as I always intended. 

Far too often, we count ourselves out and are the very ones who don’t give ourselves the opportunity to thrive. My hope is that my story can serve as a reminder that we are all always capable of more and at the very least, give yourself a fighting chance by having faith in yourself and in the process. There are no losses, only lessons. By taking action, you’re only creating new opportunities, even if it’s not the one you were aiming for. You never know what lies ahead, and will never know if you don’t even try.

As always, know your damn worth. But more important, know how to advocate for it 🤝

The honor of a lifetime to have served in the Wu Administration for the City of Boston.

I first met Michelle Wu when I was a young staffer for Speaker Bob DeLeo and she was a young City Councilor. It was obvious then that she was a special leader. 

So when she called and asked if I’d serve on her AAPI steering committee for her Mayoral run, I immediately said yes. 

After her historical win, I didn’t immediately join the team. But the time came and it started by first meeting with the Mayors amazing Chief of Staff, Tiffany Chu. Honestly, it didn’t need a lot of convincing to join the team, but for what it’s worth, Tiffany is great at recruiting.

So as I wrap my time in City Hall, I want to shout out some dear friends.

I’ll start with my people from before the win: Mary Lou, Jessicah, Brionna, Segun, Julia & Julia, Sharon, Anshi, Anthony, Dave, Enrique, and Mari. Day One’s on the WuTrain. Love yall and always there for each of you no matter what.

Next are City Hall folks who I’ve met and consider family. There are too many to name, but yall know who you are and I’m just a phone call away.

The older I get, the more you learn how rare it is to work for someone and a mission that is as special as the one being carried out under this administration. There is so much that goes into the day to day, but more so to build a new vision for a historic city. More often than not, there are more people who don’t understand and much of the work is under appreciated. It’s just the reality of public service. But when you get to work for a leader such as Michelle Wu, it’s that rare opportunity that the impossible becomes possible, and hope transforms into reality. 

To my colleagues, my last message is, don’t forget. Don’t forget why you got inspired to go into public service. Don’t forget why it was this administration in particular that called you to serve. Don’t forget that this is a generational leader who we have to rally around and not miss this opportunity to build her vision. Don’t forget that none of this is possible without your dedication and heart for the people. And finally, don’t forget about me, because I certainly won’t and will always be there for you all.

I’m proud to announce that starting this week, I’ll be joining The Asian American Foundation as the Director of Government Relations.

TAAF is dedicated to building a safer, more inclusive future for AAPIs everywhere.

Founded in response to the rise in anti-Asian hate and violence, TAAF is reversing the longstanding under-investment in our community and addressing the root causes of hate and discrimination.

Our mission is to serve the Asian American and Pacific Islander community in their pursuit of belonging and prosperity that is free from discrimination, slander, and violence.

Our vision is an America where opportunities to participate in all aspects of society are equally accessible, and individuals and communities are not rendered invisible, nor singled out for false stereotypes, discrimination, or hate on the basis of race.

It’s an honor to serve the community alongside so many amazing leaders that have built the foundation at TAAF before me.

I wanted to give a special shout out to Howard Ou, my predecessor and dear friend. Truly one of the best human beings I know. I have impossibly big shoes to fill and will do my best to make you proud. 

I also thought this picture was particularly appropriate. It’s a Boston photo of leaders who I have worked alongside for many years. Leaders who I have deep admiration for and look forward to continue building with in the coming years.

To my new teammates, I can’t wait to get to work with you all. I’m fired up and ready to rock 🫡

When we were building @1587sneakers, we were adamant that we had to be a brand that gave back. That we weren’t just about our bottom line, but something far greater and impactful for our community.

To us, it means building a brand that makes our community undeniable. One that unapologetically celebrates our heritage and our culture. But just as important, it means amplifying other amazing Asian American brands every chance we get. That means, looking to work with other Asian American brands such as our merchandiser, @awolprintshop. That means sharing our blueprint and how we succeeded, but also our mishaps along the way.

We think a mistake brands make is that the only way to give back is financially. Which is great, we plan to do the same to nonprofits through our shirt sales. We also hope to be successful enough to be even more generous. 

But in the meantime, we can find impactful ways and that’s sharing our knowledge, resources, and platform. It’s why I always visibly wear other Asian American brands. Why we look to collaborate and share space with other Asian American brands. Because we aren’t just the only dope brand to exist, many have before us, many do now, and many will come after us. We’re just here to support and build with them 🙏

Bringing back this old post since today is Korean American Day 🇰🇷

“Growing up as an Asian Americans, and Korean American specifically can be very challenging. Discovering your identity while balancing multiple cultures, languages, traditions, and values is complicated. We’re a people that has a deep and long history. There is so much pride and also pain that comes with being Korean. Then add the layers of finding your place in America.

But something that is absolutely clear to me is that no matter how “Korean” you are perceived to be or not, every one of us is enough. Nobody is “too Korean” or “not Korean enough”. Nobody, whether they are Korean or not determines that for you.”
